<p>
  My first encounter with Elixir was the humble <code>FizzBuzz</code>. It is a
  tiny problem, but it shows off two things I immediately liked about the
  language: pattern matching and the pipe operator. Here is the whole program.
</p>

<%= render CodeBlockComponent.new(language: "elixir", source: <<~ELIXIR) %>
  defmodule FizzBuzz do
    def play(n) do
      1..n
      |> Enum.map(&label/1)
      |> Enum.join(" ")
    end

    defp label(i) when rem(i, 15) == 0, do: "FizzBuzz"
    defp label(i) when rem(i, 3) == 0, do: "Fizz"
    defp label(i) when rem(i, 5) == 0, do: "Buzz"
    defp label(i), do: Integer.to_string(i)
  end
ELIXIR

<p>
  Instead of <code>if/else</code> chains, each case of <code>label/1</code> is a
  separate function clause guarded by a condition. Elixir tries them top to
  bottom and runs the first one that matches. Below is the exact same program,
  reimplemented in JavaScript — change <em>n</em> and run it.
</p>

<%= render PlaygroundComponent.new(id: "fizzbuzz", title: "FizzBuzz (JavaScript port)") do %>
  <label class="flex items-center gap-2">
    <span>n =</span>
    <input id="fizzbuzz-n" type="number" min="1" max="100" value="15"
      class="w-24 rounded-md border border-zinc-300 px-2 py-1 dark:border-zinc-600 dark:bg-zinc-900">
  </label>
<% end %>

<script>
  (() => {
    const root = document.getElementById("fizzbuzz");
    if (!root) return;
    const out = root.querySelector("[data-playground-output]");

    const label = (i) =>
      i % 15 === 0 ? "FizzBuzz" :
      i % 3 === 0  ? "Fizz" :
      i % 5 === 0  ? "Buzz" :
      String(i);

    const play = (n) =>
      Array.from({ length: n }, (_, k) => label(k + 1)).join(" ");

    root.querySelector("[data-playground-run]").addEventListener("click", () => {
      const n = Math.max(1, Math.min(100, Number(root.querySelector("#fizzbuzz-n").value) || 1));
      out.textContent = play(n);
    });
  })();
</script>

<p>
  That is the loop I will keep repeating throughout this series: write a small
  Elixir program, then port it to JavaScript so you can poke at it right here in
  the browser. Next time we will pattern-match our way through recursion.
</p>
